did.abstract: The papers consist of correspondence, government documents, writings, speeches, photographs, research materials, printed matter, motion picture film, and other material which document William C. Bullitt's career as a diplomat and journalist and his personal and family life.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: The materials previously deposited by Anne Moen Bullitt and her Estate were donated to Manuscripts and Archives by the William C. Bullitt Foundation, Inc., in 2008; gift of William C. Bullitt Foundation, Inc., 2013; gift of Nili Museum-Beit Aaronsohn, 2013.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Original audiovisual materials, as well as preservation and duplicating masters, may not be played. Researchers must consult use copies, or if none exist must pay for a use copy, which is retained by the repository. Researchers wishing to obtain an additional copy for their personal use should consult Copying Services information on the Manuscripts and Archives web site.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: Copyright has been transferred to Yale University for unpublished materials authored or otherwise produced by William Christian Bullitt and Anne Moen Bullitt in this collection. Unpublished materials authored or otherwise produced by Louise Bryant are in the public domain. Copyright status for other collection materials is unknown. Transmission or reproduction of materials protected by U.S. Copyright Law (Title 17, U.S.C.) beyond that allowed by fair use requires the written permission of the copyright owners. Works not in the public domain cannot be commercially exploited without permission of the copyright owners. Responsibility for any use rests exclusively with the user.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Copies of commercially produced audiovisual materials contained in this collection cannot be made for researcher use outside of the repository.

Original born digital files, as well as preservation masters, may not be accessed due to their fragility. Researchers must consult use copies, or if none exist request that they be made. Born digital files cannot be accessed remotely. System requirements include a Manuscripts and Archives computer and file viewing software.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Arranged in seven series and four additions: I. Correspondence, 1882-1967. II. Diplomatic and Public Papers, 1813-1956. III. Writings, 1888-1984. IV. Photographs, 1891-1964. V. Motion Pictures and Sound Recordings, 1933-1952. VI. Personal and Family Papers, 1840-1998. VII. Printed Matter, 1882-1965.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The collection provides a rich resource for the study of Bullitt's career as a diplomat and public servant. Although this collection constitutes what Bullitt considered his personal files and hence does not contain a comprehensive record of his official service, it contains extensive material related to his government work. It provides a more intimate or mundane view of his activities through private correspondence with his colleagues, personnel records, photographs, and files related to travel, social events, and purchases. However, there is also a wide selection of memoranda, official telegrams, and reports that can be found in Series II or as enclosures to correspondence in Series I. There is material relevant to his service as Ambassador to the Soviet Union (1933-1936), Ambassador to France (1936-1940), Ambassador-at-large (1941-1942), Special Assistant to the Secretary of the Navy (1942-1943), and his two stints as Special Assistant to the Secretary of State (1917-1919 and 1933). Information about Bullitt's involvement with American negotiations on the recognition of the Soviet Union can be found in Series II, his mentoring of George F. Kennan in Series I and II, his reports to Franklin Roosevelt on conditions in France and around Europe during the outbreak of World War II in Series I, and wartime advice to Roosevelt on how to handle the Soviet Union in Series I and II. Unlike the files from Bullitt's service with the Roosevelt administration, the materials from his work with the Wilson administration, his 1943 campaign for mayor of Philadelphia, and his 1948 investigation into American aid to China for the Joint Congressional Committee on Foreign Economic Cooperation provide a much more comprehensive picture of these public undertakings.

Beyond his work as a public servant, the collection documents his efforts as an author and journalist through a substantial body of drafts, notes, related correspondence and research materials, and unpublished manuscripts of a novel, plays, short stories, and a screenplay. There is extensive material concerning Thomas Woodrow Wilson , the psychological study of the former president which Bullitt co-authored with Sigmund Freud, including several chapter manuscripts and fragments in Freud's hand, and an unpublished book-length biography of Wilson written by Bullitt. The collection also contains much material relevant to Bullitt's work as a journalist in the 1910s, 1940s, and 1950s. Since his later journalism is concerned largely with the threat of communism and the Soviet Union, there is extensive information about these issues in Series I and II, as well as material documenting his ties to Nationalist China, Korea, and Vietnam and his interest in European unification.

The papers provide copious biographical material about William C. Bullitt throughout his life although the materials are much thinner on his youth before 1909. There is also a small amount of material concerning Louise Bryant, Bullitt's second wife, including correspondence in Series I, photographs in Series IV, and subject files in Series VI.

The collection also includes a small amount of materials relating to Bullitt's daughter Anne Moen Bullitt, consisting of personal correspondence and photographs, correspondence with researchers interested in her parents, and materials relating to her fourth husband, Daniel Brewster.

The materials that comprise the William C. Bullitt papers originally arrived at Yale between 2003 and 2005 with the papers of Louise Bryant as part of a deposit from their daughter Anne Moen Bullitt. The Bullitt papers constituted the vast majority of this deposit, but since most of the Bryant material had been stored separately and it appeared to be papers originally collected and saved by Bryant, not by her daughter or Bullitt, the Louise Bryant papers became a separate collection maintained in Manuscripts and Archives at the Yale University Library. A small portion of the Bryant papers were intermingled with the Bullitt materials. An effort was made to separate this intermixed material, but some Bryant material may remain in the Bullitt papers and vice versa. All of the correspondence between Bullitt and Bryant was kept with the Bullitt papers. Photographs of Bullitt, which do not picture Bryant, have been removed from the Bryant papers and unified with other photographs of him in the Bullitt papers.

A small portion of the Bullitt papers concerning World War I and the Paris Peace Conference had previously been on deposit at Yale until 1967 when Anne Bullitt removed them upon her father's death. (See Series II) Before the Bullitt papers came to Yale in 2004, the bulk of them were housed in several filing cabinets and trunks in his daughter's home in Ireland. A smaller portion of the collection came from Bullitt's farm in Ashfield, Massachusetts. Much of the material arrived in labelled folders and most of this folder arrangement and the folder titles were retained. However, there was little apparent structure to the files above the folder level, and so an organization scheme was imposed by archivists. Most of Bullitt's correspondence arrived in folders arranged alphabetically within each year. In order to create a single alphabetical run for the correspondence, all of the correspondence was sorted, alphabetized, and refoldered by archivists. Correspondents with whom Bullitt exchanged more than approximately five letters received individually labeled folders.

separatedmaterial.head: Separated Materials
separatedmaterial.p: The photographic copies of the Aaron Aaronsohn diaries from the original accession in boxes 173-175 were discarded due to poor condition and replaced by PDF print copies provided by Nili Museum-Beit Aaronsohn in 2013.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: William Christian Bullitt, Jr. was born in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, on January 25, 1891. He was the first child of the wealthy lawyer William Christian Bullitt Sr. and his wife Louisa Horwitz Bullitt. Bullitt attended the DeLancy prepatory school before enrolling at Yale University. He joined the Class of 1912, but a year's absence due to illness delayed his graduation until 1913 (Phi Beta Kappa, Townsend Debating Prize, Scroll and Key Society, Dramatic Association, Yale Daily News . He attended Harvard Law School for less than a year and left after his father died in 1914. For the second half of 1914, he traveled extensively throughout Europe including Germany, Russia, France, and Great Britain. Returning to Philadelphia, he joined the staff of the Philadelphia Ledger where he rose to the positions of Washington correspondent, associate editor, and foreign correspondent. In 1915, he accompanied Henry Ford's peace expedition to Europe and gained recognition for his reporting on Ford's efforts to facilitate a peace settlement. The following year Bullitt married Aimée Ernesta Drinker of Philadelphia.

Bullitt began his career as a diplomat in December 1917 when he joined the State Department as a special assistant to the secretary. There he was appointed chief of the Bureau of Central European Information, which produced weekly intelligence reports on the European powers. In December 1918, he sailed to France to serve as an attaché to the American Commission to Negotiate the Peace and chief of the Division of Current Intelligence at the Paris Peace Conference. Under instructions from Secretary of State Robert Lansing, Bullitt undertook a secret mission to Russia in February 1919 to investigate conditions there, accompanied by the journalist Lincoln Steffens. After the mission, Bullitt grew critical of President Wilson's plans for a post-war peace settlement, resigned from the State Department, and testified against the Treaty of Versailles before the Senate.

From 1919 to 1933, William Bullitt withdrew from government service. In 1921, he was managing editor for the Famous Players-Lasky Corporation in New York City. He spent the rest of this period writing and traveling, splitting his time between his farm in Ashfield, Massachusetts, Philadelphia, Paris, Turkey, and various tours through Europe. In addition to a number of unpublished plays, short stories, and a screenplay, Bullitt published a satirical novel It's Not Done (1926) about upperclass society in Philadelphia and wrote another novel "The Divine Wisdom" which was never published. Sometime after meeting Sigmund Freud in the mid-1920s, Bullitt began a collaboration with the doctor to write a psychological analysis of Woodrow Wilson. By 1932, the book manuscript was finished, but it would remain unpublished until 1966. After divorcing Aimée Ernesta Drinker, he married the journalist Louise Bryant in 1923 who gave birth to their daughter Anne Moen Bullitt the following year. In 1930, Bullitt divorced Bryant and won sole custody of Anne.

After the election of Franklin D. Roosevelt, Bullitt returned to the State Department in 1933 as a special assistant to the secretary. He served as the executive officer for the American delegation to the London Monetary and Economic Conference of 1933 and assisted with negotiations for American diplomatic recognition of the Soviet Union, meeting repeatedly with the Soviet Commissar for Foreign Affairs Maxim Litvinov. In November 1933, Roosevelt appointed Bullitt the first U.S. Ambassador to the Soviet Union, and he arrived in Moscow to a warm welcome by Soviet leaders. During his time in Moscow, Bullitt established the embassy and mentored a later generation of American Soviet experts including George F. Kennan and Loy W. Henderson, who served on the embassy staff. Relations with the Soviets cooled quickly and Bullitt found himself virtually ignored by Stalin's government. In August 1936, Bullitt became the ambassador to France and established extraordinarily close and cordial relations with French leaders. As tensions mounted in Europe in the late 1930s, Bullitt regularly reported directly to Roosevelt on developments in France and its neighbors. When the Germans invaded France and the government fled Paris for Bourdeaux, Bullitt remained behind and, because of his popularity with the French, was appointed provisional mayor of Paris until the Germans occupied the city. He returned to the United States in July 1940 to advocate American intervention in the war, giving a widely publicized speech at the American Philosophical Society in Philadelphia.

Unsuccessful at securing a higher office in the Roosevelt administration, Bullitt held the position of ambassador-at-large in 1941. Early in 1942, Roosevelt sent him to North Africa and the Middle East on a fact-finding mission. In June 1942, he took the position of special assistant to Secretary of the Navy Frank Knox. There he wrote several long memoranda for Roosevelt advising the president on plans for the post-war peace settlement and warning of the threat the Soviet Union and international communism continued to pose. In the early 1940s, Bullitt was also urging Roosevelt to dismiss the Under Secretary of State Sumner Welles because of Welles's homosexuality. Welles resigned in 1943. In August 1943, Bullitt left the Roosevelt administration to run as the Democratic Party candidate for the mayor of Philadelphia, but lost in the general election. Frustrated in his attempts to join the American armed forces, Bullitt served as a commandant and aide to General Jean de Lattre de Tassigny in the Free French Armed Forces until the end of the war.

Bullitt spent the next nine years as a journalist and writer on current affairs. The major theme of his writing was the danger of communism. In his 1946 book The Great Globe Itself , he criticized Roosevelt's policies toward the Soviet Union which Bullitt viewed as surrendering large parts of the world including Eastern Europe to Stalin's communist dictatorship. Bullitt wrote articles for Life , Reader's Digest , Time , and Look magazines, most based on his visits to Taiwan, Korea, Vietnam, India, Hong Kong, and the Philippines. He had especially close ties to Taiwan including a friendship with Generalissimo and Madame Chiang Kai-shek and a house he maintained there in the early 1950s. In 1948, the Joint Congressional Committee on Foreign Economic Cooperation requested his assistance as a consultant to write a report on the Economic Cooperation Agency and American aid to China. In the late 1950s and early 1960s, Bullitt primarily concerned himself with his family and friends, his farm in Ashfield, Massachusetts, and his other private business interests. He died of leukemia in Neuilly, France, on February 15, 1967.
Will Brownell and Richard N. Billings, So Close to Greatness: A Biography of William C. Bullitt (New York: Macmillan, 1987).

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The correspondence is arranged alphabetically. It is primarily made up of incoming letters to Bullitt with their enclosures and copies of letters Bullitt sent, but in rare cases material has been filed under names as if the name were a subject heading. The letters document his social and family life, his career as a diplomat, and his work as journalist and author, especially his efforts to oppose communism. The correspondence reflects Bullitt's acquaintance with an extraordinary variety of prominent political and cultural figures from the United States, Europe, and Asia in the twentieth century. A substantial portion of the correspondence in this series is actually signed and written by Carmel Offie, a long-time aide and friend of Bullitt. Most of this is written on Bullitt's behalf or concerns his affairs, but a small portion of it is Offie's personal correspondence.

Most of the letters concern Bullitt's social and family life and his personal affairs. There is extensive correspondence with his daughter Anne, his mother Louisa H., and his brother Orville. Other relatives with substantial correspondence include his aunt Alice Forbers Perkins Hooper, William Marshall Bullitt, and his cousins Nancy Astor, Thomas W. Bullitt, and Orville Horwitz. There are numerous letters from his first wife Aimée Ernesta Drinker Bullitt and between Bullitt and his second wife Louise Bryant. The Bryant folders contain both original incoming and outgoing letters because correspondence from the Bullitt and Bryant papers at Yale have been unified in this collection. Much of the correspondence between Carmel Offie and Bullitt concerns Offie's reports about European politics in 1946. There is also correspondence from the couple, Edith E. and Harold Hartwell, who ran Bullitt's farm in Ashfield, Massachusetts. Material related to Bullitt's legal matters can be found among the correspondence with R. Sturgis Ingersoll. For Bullitt's finances, see the correspondence with Thomas Raeburn White and Platt, Yungman, and Company. Personal friends whose correspondence is substantially represented in this series include Richard Robbins, William V. and Isabel Griffin, Jesse H. Jones, Max Kastnor, Joseph Reed, Max Shoop, and Fritz Meyer.

This series also contains much that is relevant to Bullitt's years of government service, especially his work as a diplomat, even though the correspondence it contains appears to have been separated by Bullitt and his assistants, due to its more personal nature, from official correspondence, which Bullitt presumably deposited with the State and Navy Departments. There is an extensive correspondence with Franklin D. Roosevelt concentrated around the years that Bullitt served as ambassador to France (1936-1940) reflecting their friendship and the information Bullitt provided the president on European developments on the eve of World War II. The Roosevelt correspondence includes photocopies of letters between Roosevelt and Bullitt which were made at the Roosevelt Presidential Library. Apparently, Anne Bullitt added these copies to Bullitt's existing files when she was collaborating with Orville Bullitt on the publication of the edited volume of Roosevelt-Bullitt correspondence that Orville Bullitt assembled after his brother's death. Further material on Bullitt's relationship with Roosevelt can be found in the extensive correspondence with the president's secretary Marguerite LeHand. Bullitt's correspondence with his mentor in the State Department in the 1930s, R. Walton Moore, is particularly extensive and much of it concerns diplomacy with the Soviet Union including Moore's reports on debt negotiations in Washington with the Soviet Commissar for Foreign Affairs Maxim Litvinov and Ambassador Alexander Troyanovsky. Other material concerning diplomacy with the Soviet Union and Bullitt's ambassadorship there can be found in the correspondence of John C. Wiley, George F. Kennan, Loy W. Henderson, John Cudahy, George S. Messersmith, Maxim Litvinov, William E. Dodd, Albert F. Ceres, Jr., Harrie T. Lindeberg, Charles E. Stuart, and John Van A. MacMurray. Material related to Bullitt's work as ambassador to France and the outbreak of World War II can be found in the correspondence of Edwin C. Wilson, Anthony J. Drexel Biddle, Jr., Hugh Wilson, Jean Monnet, Leon Blum, Suzanne Blum, Alfred Bergman, Sumner Welles, William Phillipps, Edouard Daladier, John C. Wiley, H. Freeman Matthews, Alexander C. Kirk, Myron Taylor, Jesse Isidor Straus, and William Wasserman. Concerning wartime diplomacy and other war related issues, see the correspondence of Cordell Hull, Roscoe H. Hillenkoetter, Frank Knox, Edward R. Stettinius, F. H. LaGuardia, and Douglas MacArthur II. Other diplomats and public officials with whom Bullitt had substantive correspondences about various issues include Louis B. Wehle, Henry Morganthau Jr., Felix Frankfurter, Harold L. Ickes, Bernard Baruch, Francis B. Biddle, Thomas D. White, Allen W. Dulles, James V. Forrestal, J. Edgar Hoover, Joseph P. Kennedy, Richard M. Nixon, Alfred E. Smith, George H. Earle, James A. Farley, Henry Cabot Lodge, Jr., Robert A. Lovett, James Kimble Vardaman Jr., Joseph C. Grew, William Averell Harriman, Angus Ward, David H. Morris, Robert D. Murphy, Stanley Hornbeck, and S. Pinckney Tuck.

The writing and publication of Thomas Woodrow Wilson as well as Sigmund Freud's emigration from Austria is discussed in the correspondence among Bullitt, Sigmund Freud, and Anna Freud. Other correspondence with Sigmund Freud, Anna Freud, and Ernst Freud about Thomas Woodrow Wilson can be found in Series II. Bullitt's work as a journalist is discussed in the correspondence with Henry R. Luce, Life Magazine , Time Inc., DeWitt Wallace, and Reader's Digest . A substantial amount of material concerns Bullitt's opposition to communism, especially in the late 1940s and 1950s, and can be found in the correspondence with Clarence K. Streit, Alfred Kohlberg, Douglas H. Allen, Laurence B. Keiser, Charles T. Mayer, Leopold Braun, Francis Spellman, Styles Bridges, E. W. Capen, William Henry Chamberlain, S. M. Levitas, Albert C. Wedemeyer, Upton Sinclair, Dwight D. Eisenhower, William F. Knowland, and Eugene Lyons. Bullitt's ties to Taiwan are represented in his correspondence with Chang Ming-kai, Pai Shiu Chuan, Sampson C. Shen, Pei Tsuyee, V. K. Wellington Koo, General Sun Li-jen, George Kungchao Yeh, Generalissimo and Madame Chiang Kai-shek, Konsin C. Shah, and Karl L. Rankin; to Korea, in his correspondence with Whang Ey Chan, Syngman Rhee; and to Vietnam, in his correspondence with Do Van Bong. His interests in a united Europe are documented in his correspondence with Richard N. Coudenhove-Kalergi. Bullitt also assisted a number of individuals in their immigration to the United States which is reflected in the correspondence of Stefan Osusky and Pai Shiu Chuan, among others.

Bullitt's friendship with a number of prominent composers, artists, and writers is represented in the correspondence with Marsden Hartley, George Antheil, John Barber, George Biddle, Archibald MacLeish, Lincoln Steffens, William Carlos Williams, Upton Sinclair, Oswald Garrison Villard, Max Eastman, William Shirer, and Lincoln Colcord. For material on Bullitt's campaign for mayor of Philadelphia in 1943, see the files for Albert F. Ceres and James P. Clark.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains materials relating to William Bullitt's diplomatic career and the other public services he performed throughout his life. The papers include official documents, reports, memoranda, and administrative and research material. They are arranged by subject and by the official positions held by Bullitt into ten sections, listed in rough chronological order: World War I and the Paris Peace Conference; Special Assistant to the Secretary of State; Ambassador to the USSR; Ambassador to France; Ambassador-at-large; Special Assistant to the Secretary of the Navy; Philadelphia mayoral campaign; Free French Armed Forces;Joint Congressional Committee on Foreign Economic Cooperation (China); and Miscellaneous. For additional material related to Bullitt's years of public service, see the Notes and Speeches sections of Series III and Series IV.

The World War I and the Paris Peace Conference materials pertain to Bullitt's service as an Assistant Secretary of State (1917-1918) responsible for producing intelligence reports on European powers and his appointment as an attaché to the American Commission to Negotiate the Peace (1918-1919). In the latter capacity, Bullitt undertook a secret mission to investigate conditions in Russia. The materials include memoranda, intelligence reports, and a large series of weekly State Department reports which summarize current intelligence about the Allied, Neutral, and Central Powers. This section has two sub-sections: original deposit and supplement. Most of these records were originally deposited by Bullitt at Yale as part of the Edward M. House Collection. In 1967, after William Bullitt's death, his daughter Anne removed this original deposit, but most of these materials were returned to Yale in 2003. Almost all of the missing material was reproduced from a microfilm copy of the original deposit that Yale had made and kept closed to researchers. One folder of missing material labeled "Zionism" could not be recreated from microfilm. The material from the original deposit has been left as it had been arranged in 1967 with the exception of the alphabetized correspondence which has been integrated into Series I. A small supplement of similar materials expands the original deposit but is arranged in its own sub-section.

Most of the correspondence, memoranda, and notes that comprise the Special Assistant to the Secretary of State files concern Bullitt's participation in the London Economic Conference of 1933 and his negotiations with Soviet officials about the recognition of the USSR by the United States.

Materials from Bullitt's ambassadorship to the Soviet Union mainly relate to the operation of the embassy and to the ambassador's travels like his 1934 meeting with Chiang Kai-shek. Personnel files include descriptions of the performance of the embassy staff including George F. Kennan. Two longer memoranda address the situation in North China and the Communist International. The files in this section contain few of the embassy's communications with the State Department and little about the implemenation of American policy toward the Soviet Union or the delegation's relations with Soviet officials beyond issues surrounding the establishment and daily functioning of the embassy.

The records from Bullitt's service as ambassador to France primarily concern the rountine operation of the embassy, the embassy's social events, and the ambassador's travel around France. There are personnel files and an extensive collection of personal correspondence of Bullitt's close aide Carmel Offie. A small selection of memoranda address various topics including political developments around Europe. These files contain few of the embassy's communications with the State Department.

The Ambassador-at-large files contain materials that document Bullitt's mission to North Africa and the Middle East in 1941 and his engagement with other war-related issues such as transportation routes from West Africa and civil defense. There are also documents related to Bullitt's directorship of the General Aniline and Film Corporation. The Special Assistant to the Secretary of the Navy files contain memoranda and policy papers for President Roosevelt and Secretary Knox, including Bullitt's advice for post-war policy and relations with the Soviet Union; a diary of Bullitt's participation in a 1942 London war conference; and memoranda about the Navy and various foreign policy topics.

The extensive materials on Bullitt's 1943 Philadelphia mayoral campaign include correspondence, speeches, subject files, and clippings which thoroughly document the negative campaign tactics used against Bullitt. The small section of materials on his service in the Free French Armed Forces includes correspondence and his military orders. The records concerning Bullitt's work as a consultant to the Joint Congressional Committee on Foreign Economic Cooperation are made up primarily of research materials for his 1948 report on American aid to China and the Economic Cooperation Administration's role in China. The Miscellaneous section of this series includes memoranda on discussions with President Eisenhower about Indochina and Secretary of State Dulles about Korea and a collection of reports written by Bullitt about the Soviet Union.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series is comprised of original writings by Bullitt and others. It is organized into nine sections: Books, Journalism, Notes, Plays, Screenplay, Short stories, Speeches, Writings by others, and Unidentified manuscripts.

The Books section contains drafts, clippings, and correspondence related to Bullitt's three published works: his critique of American policy toward the Soviet Union, The Great Globe Itself (1946), his novel, It's Not Done (1926), and his psychological study of Woodrow Wilson co-authored with Sigmund Freud, Thomas Woodrow Wilson (1966). The materials concerning Thomas Woodrow Wilson include manuscripts in Freud's hand, correspondence with Freud, various drafts, correspondence with publishers, and research materials. Some of the correspondence with publishers post-dates Bullitt's death and was apparently handled by his daughter Anne. The research materials include a 300-page manuscript biography of Woodrow Wilson written by Bullitt, most of which is unpublished. Only a small portion concerning Wilson's youth was published as a digest in the book. The manuscript biography apparently served as the empirical basis for Freud's and Bullitt's psychological analysis of Wilson. There are also drafts of Bullitt's unpublished novel "The Divine Wisdom," an incomplete memoir manuscript written in 1950 entitled "The Shining Adventure," and materials concerning other uncompleted book projects.

The materials concerning Bullitt's career as a journalist, both before and after his work as a diplomat, are divided into two sub-sections: Articles and Research materials. The Articles files are organized by title and include mostly drafts but some contain related notes and copies of the final published version. The folders titled "Ford peace expedition" include a short diary kept by Bullitt, photographs, several copies of a satirical newsletter The Argosy produced by reporters on the trip, and other related printed matter, as well as notes and drafts from the articles Bullitt wrote about Ford's voyage. The Research materials contain printed matter, reports, notes, memoranda, and correspondence that appear to relate to topics Bullitt wrote about as a journalist in the late 1940s and early 1950s, most having to do with the threat of communism in East Asia and France. The large number of folders titled "Reference" contain printed matter, organized in rough chronological order, which appear to concern primarily the subjects of Bullitt's journalism.

The Speeches section includes copies and drafts of Bullitt's published and unpublished speeches arranged chronologically and correspondence from the public in response to a 1940 speech he gave in Philadelphia which advocated American intervention in World War II. Many of the speech folders contain notes, clippings, and other materials that primarily relate to Bullitt's speeches, but also to his other journalistic or literary writings. The Plays, Poems, Screenplay, and Short Stories files document Bullitt's literary efforts beyond his novel writing and apparently none of this material has ever been published. The Notes section contains material related to Bullitt's work as a diplomat and journalist, his literary efforts, and his personal life. The notes have not been arranged by date or subject. Writings by others is made up of drafts and manuscripts by authors other than Bullitt including Paul Reynaud and William Langer. The Unidentified manuscripts are writings that cannot be readily identified as the work of Bullitt or another author. They are arranged by date although a majority of them are undated.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series consists of photographic prints, negatives, and photo albums. The vast majority of the photographs are black and white and most are in fair condition. The series is organized into two sections: Diplomatic-public service and Personal. Within the Diplomatic and public service section, the materials are arranged by position held by Bullitt and by subject. Within the personal section, the materials are organized by subject. The few negatives in the series are filed along with the photographic prints and albums. The photographs document William Bullitt's career as a diplomat, his social and family life, and his work as a journalist in the 1940s and 1950s reporting on world affairs, especially in Asia.

The bulk of the photographs concerning Bullitt's diplomatic and public service relate to his ambassadorships to the Soviet Union from 1933 to 1936 and to France from 1936 to 1940. Most of the Soviet Union images picture Bullitt with unidentified groups or individuals; some of these appear to involve government business or Soviet officials but with many it is unclear. Only a small portion of these photographs are specifically identified. These include captioned press photographs of Ambassador Bullitt's arrival in the USSR in December 1933 and his welcome by Michael Kalinin and other Soviet officials as well as Ambassador Bullitt playing polo with Soviet soldiers. A much greater proportion of the photographs from Bullitt's service in France are identified. Many of these are captioned press photographs of Bullitt meeting with French officials, participating in ceremonies, and generally performing his duties as ambassador. Other identified photographs include the June 1940 bombardment of Paris, Bullitt's 1938 visit to Lorraine, and the 1937 visit to France of Sara Roosevelt, Franklin D. Roosevelt's mother. Besides the material related to his ambassadorships, there are small numbers of photographs concerning Bullitt's particiation in the Paris Peace Conference of 1919, his candidacy for the mayor of Philadelphia, and his service as an Ambassador-at-large, a Special Assistant to the Secretary of the Navy, and a military aide in the Free French Armed Forces.

This series also contains a large selection of photographs related to Bullitt's social and family life. A variety of photographs depict him throughout his life from infancy into retirement. Family pictures include those of his extended family, his first wife Aimée Ernesta Drinker Bullitt, his second wife Louise Bryant, his daughter Anne, and Refik Ishmail, a Turkish boy who lived with the Bullitt family. Other photographs picture friends and professional acquaintances including Bullitt's long-time friend and aide Carmel Offie. A large number of photographs relate to Camp Pasquaney, a New Hampshire summer camp Bullitt attended as a boy. Among the personal photographs are included images from Bullitt's travels to East Asia in the late 1940s and 1950s as a journalist. These photographs capture his visits to South Korea, Japan, Indochina, and the Philippines and some of the unidentified photographs may picture other countries like Taiwan where Bullitt spent a good deal of time. A large portion of the images from the Far East depict Bullitt meeting with American and Asian military personnel.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains motion picture film and a sound recording that document Bullitt's diplomatic career and personal life. The five 35mm films appear to date from the 1930s when Bullitt was ambassador to the Soviet Union and then France and relate to various aspects of his time in those positions. The sound recording is of a 1952 address broadcast from a Yankton, South Dakota radio station in which Bullitt expresses his support for the candidacy of Robert Taft to be the Republican Party nominee for president.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series is divided into Personal papers and Family papers. The personal papers are comprised of Bullitt's legal, financial, and medical documents, subject files, appointment books, school papers, address books, membership cards, drawings, objects, and other materials of a personal nature. The legal documents include wills, passports, and deeds and the financial material includes Bullitt's personal financial records, such as bank statements, bills, receipts, and checkbooks, from his service as ambassador to the Soviet Union and France. The large assortment of appointment books document Bullitt's daily activities from the start of his ambassadorship in France to the end of his life with occasional gaps.

The subject files reflect Bullitt's personal, political, and journalistic interests. The larger subject files concern his involvement with Georgetown University, his support for a unified Europe, and ties to Taiwan including a file on Chang Ming-kai, a servant employed by Bullitt whose treatment by General Chang Quo-chang became the subject of controversy between Bullitt and Chiang Kai-shek. Three folders of material address Bullitt's involvement in the resignation of Sumner Welles and contain evidence Bullitt gathered that Welles had made criminal homosexual advances on railroad porters. Because the Welles folders contain notes written in the hand of Anne Bullitt and other material apparently added by her after her father's death, it is not clear if these files were originally assembled by William Bullitt or by Anne gathering together materials largely from her father's papers. There is also a small amount of material in the subject files concerning Louise Bryant and Bullitt's divorce from her.

The family papers are made up of correspondence, writings by Bullitt's parents, and materials collected by Anne Bullitt. The correspondence consists of letters between Bullitt relatives that are neither to nor from William C. Bullitt, Jr, and much of it predates Bullitt's birth. Included in the material collected by Anne are correspondence, family history research, photographs, legal documents, and printed matter. Most of the material concerns her parents William C. Bullitt, Jr. and Louise Bryant. This includes correspondence with researchers interested in her parents and other correspondence specifically concerning the biography published about her father So Close to Greatness and the revisions she demanded under the threat of a lawsuit. The last folder of "Researchers" correspondence contains a detailed bibliography concerning Bullitt. There is also correspondence with her uncle Orville H. Bullitt about the book, For the President, Personal and Secret, he edited, which contained Bullitt's correspondence with President Franklin Roosevelt. Anne's materials also include correspondence with her fourth husband Senator Daniel Brewster and a large selection of his publicity photographs.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series consists of printed and published material collected by Bullitt, which is arranged by type of material. It includes inscribed books, press clippings, pamphlets, Congressional publications, magazines, maps, and other matter. The most common subjects that the clippings address are Bullitt's support for American intervention in World War II, his warnings about the post-World War II peace settlement and the threat of communism, communism in China, World War I, and his appointment as ambassador to the Soviet Union.
